{"key":"processedPost-15312574","value":{"id":15312574,"first":15312337,"last":15312604,"when":1320247076,"utime":"11/02/11 06:17 PM","content":"Rotating is always good, or having it in front of a window with a light on the other side.<br /><br />Pins usually form on the opposite side of the substrate from the light.&nbsp; It's the mushroom mycelium which absorbs and uses the light during this phase, so I speculate this is a survival technique that evolved to prevent the mushrooms themselves from being scorched by the sun.<br /><br />Bear in mind, if you have a ton of pins, expect many of them to abort.&nbsp; This is normal, so don't try to fix what isn't broken when you see it.&nbsp; A substrate can only support so many fruits, so the mycelium, not you, will decide which ones to let grow and which ones to abort.<br />RR","title":"Re: and the search bar... doesnt give me my answer? :(","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}